# Submodule & Addon Abstraction Workflow

Step-by-step instructions for extracting reusable code into a shared Blender submodule, creating its development addon wrapper, and linking it into consuming addons. Use this as both an LLM primer and a living reference.

## Prerequisites

| What | Where | Purpose |
|------|-------|---------|
| Shared tools | `blender_utils/addon_tools/` | Generator CLI, build, publish, test |
| Submodule templates | `blender_utils/submodules/_template_submodule/` | Scaffold skeleton for new submodules |
| Addon template | `blender_utils/.template_addon/` | Scaffold skeleton for new addons |
| Dev addons home | `blender_addons/` | Working directory for addon development |
| Machine paths | Per-addon `local_paths.bat` (gitignored) | `BLENDER_EXE`, `BLENDER_USER_SCRIPTS`, `ADDON_TOOLS` |

All paths below are relative to the `Work_Scripts/` workspace root unless otherwise noted.

---

## Overview: What Gets Created

When abstracting code into a shared submodule, you end up with three artifacts:

```
blender_utils/submodules/<module_id>/   ← The shared submodule (standalone Python package)
blender_addons/lks_<module_id>_dev/     ← Dev wrapper addon (loads the submodule in Blender)
  └─ submodules/<module_id>/            ← Junction → blender_utils/submodules/<module_id>/
```

The submodule is the source of truth. The dev addon is a thin Blender-loadable shell whose only job is to register the submodule so you can test it in isolation. Production addons later link the same submodule via their own junction.

---

## Phase 1: Identify the Abstraction Boundary

Before scaffolding anything, define what the submodule will own.

**Checklist:**
- [ ] Name the domain clearly (e.g., "hotkey_resolver", "mesh_cleanup", "export_helpers")
- [ ] List the operators it will expose (`LKS_OT_*`)
- [ ] List the utility functions it provides (pure helpers in `util/`)
- [ ] Confirm it has **zero imports from the parent addon** — submodules are fully standalone
- [ ] Identify any scene properties it needs (`bpy.props.*` / `PropertyGroup`)
- [ ] Decide: does it need a UI panel, or just operators callable from other panels?

**Boundary rules:**
- A submodule **never** imports from the addon that hosts it
- A submodule **never** calls `bpy.ops.*` for its own operators (use direct function calls)
- A submodule **may** import from other submodules if that dependency is declared and junctioned
- Shared pure-Python utilities (no `bpy`) belong in `blender_utils/addon_tools/` or a non-Blender package — not in a submodule

