## Phase 5: Link into a Production Addon

Once the submodule works in isolation, link it into any addon that needs it.

### Using the generator

```powershell
cd C:\BTS_SSD\Work_Scripts\blender_utils
python -m addon_tools.generate link "C:\path\to\my_addon" "mesh_cleanup"
```

This creates the junction and updates `addon_config.toml`.

### Manual alternative

```powershell
cd C:\path\to\my_addon\submodules
cmd /c mklink /J mesh_cleanup "C:\BTS_SSD\Work_Scripts\blender_utils\submodules\mesh_cleanup"
```

Then add to `addon_config.toml`:
```toml
[submodules]
mesh_cleanup = "mesh_cleanup"
```

### Auto-discovery

The addon's `register_addon.py` **automatically discovers** submodules. It scans `submodules/` for directories with `__init__.py` that have `register`/`unregister` functions. No manual import wiring needed — just create the junction and it works.

---

## Phase 6: Publish

### Submodule repo
The submodule at `blender_utils/submodules/<name>/` is its own git repo. Push it to GitHub as you would any repo.

### Dev addon repo
The dev addon at `blender_addons/lks_<name>_dev/` is also its own git repo. When publishing:
- `push_remote.bat` filters files via `.remoteignore` and pushes to GitHub
- `release.bat` builds the extension zip from a clean clone — junctions are followed, so real submodule files end up in the zip
- The consumer never needs junctions — the published zip is a flat, standalone package

### Production addon
When a production addon includes the submodule, the publish pipeline (`publish_to_github.py`) uses `shutil.copytree` which follows junctions. The remote clone and final zip contain real copies of the submodule files.

